Section 1

Calculator Magic

Pick any three digit number. Write it twice in a row, as a six digit number.
No matter what you choose, this number will be divisible by 7.
Now divide again by the original number. What number do you get? Does this number change when you change your original three digit number?
x = 924
x = 924
magic = 924*1001 %This gives the same 3-digit number twice in a row
magic = 924924
nextresult = magic/7
nextresult = 132132
finalresult = nextresult/924
finalresult = 143
y = 78
y = 78
magic = y*10101
magic = 787878
disp("This magic number is divisible by 21! The result is:")
This magic number is divisible by 21! The result is:
nextresult = magic / 21
nextresult = 37518
finalresult = nextresult / y
finalresult = 481

Simple calculations, variables, scripts

script files (.m)

Scripts are a simple way of storing lines of code. We used scripts in Section 1, and older Matlab code is more often in that format.
Pro: easy to call into other files.
Pro: The file is literally plain text, you can write it in any program and run it in Matlab later.
Con: Writing in plain text requires comments. No text formatting.
Con: Outputs are saved in the command window, and must be rerun to see the result
Lec1_Intro_calc_magic %command must match file name exactly, without .m or .mlx
 
finalresult*5000
clear %clear only affects the workspace (the variables stored), not the live script outputs
disp(finalresult)
Unrecognized function or variable 'finalresult'.
clear %does not affect live script outputs, only affects workspace
clc %clear (cl) command (c) window.

Live script and Live code (.mlx and .m)

This file is a live script. It has better formatting options: You can break code into sections, and you can convert cells between Code Format and Text Format. Outputs are even saved as part of the file.
In Matlab versions R2024b and earlier, live scripts are .mlx files. These files are not plain text, but you can export the file as .html or .pdf to let others read the file.
Summer 2025 Update: Matlab version R2025a made it possible to format a plaintext .m file into a live script. Though it's easier to use Matlab directly, it can be nice to see how the code looks when we don't have access to the Matlab program.
We will mostly use live scripts for Matlab. Even the .m files can be exported as .html or .pdf
Later on, we'll look at functions and live functions.

When you place a semicolon ; at the end of a line, the line is calculated, but the output is supressed. Notice in the example below, y will not show up as an output, but it will be calculated in the workspace and you will be able to use it for future calculations, such as in myaverage.
y = 90;
myaverage = (x+y)/2 %use parentheses
myaverage = 68.5000

Exercise: create 2 vectors with 5 points equally spaced between 15 and 30.
  • Create vec1 using linspace
  • Create vec2 using the colon method
  • The outputs of vec1 and vec 2 should be equal
  • Solution is below
vec1 = linspace(15,30,5)
vec1 = 1×5
15.0000 18.7500 22.5000 26.2500 30.0000
vec2 = 15:3.75:30
vec2 = 1×5
15.0000 18.7500 22.5000 26.2500 30.0000
The lines below show the strategy for determining the count for vec2, without calculating vec1 first. In general, the count has to be
interval_length = 30-15; %distance between start and end.
num_of_spaces = 5-1; %5 points have 4 spaces between them.
spacing = interval_length/num_of_spaces %divide length equally among the spaces.
spacing = 3.7500
vec3 = 15:spacing:30
vec3 = 1×5
15.0000 18.7500 22.5000 26.2500 30.0000
v2 = 15:15/(5-1):30
v2 = 1×5
15.0000 18.7500 22.5000 26.2500 30.0000

Pointwise multiplication .*

The actual outputs are correct (see above). Outputs above are caused by scientific notation and rounding. Matlab only shows so many digits. Even if format long is enabled and shows enough digits, we still get scientific notation.

The Epsilon function is helpful for determining floating point accuracy. It measures the gap between a number and the next largest number. Any gap smaller than this is indistingushible in Matlab.
eps(pi/4) %How close is pi/4 to the next largest floating point number?

This means 2^60 + 128 is indistinguishable from 2^60 in Matlab, but Matlab can tell the difference between 2^60 + 129 and 2^60.
What about the threshold going down?

Similarly, 2^60 - 64 is indistiguishable from 2^60 in Matlab, but 2^60 - 65 is recognized as different from 2^60.
Since 256/2 = 128, A good way to think of the Eps(2^60) = 256 is that Matlab can guarantee that any number outside of the real line interval [2^60 - 128, 2^60 + 128] can be distinguished from 2^60 (note that the center of that interval is 2^60 and the length of the interval is 256). While the right side of the interval is indistinguishable from 2^60, it's not necessarily true that the left side of the interval will be.
Only a finite amount of memory (digits) can be stored for each number. Largest nonzero digits are most significant.
Specifially, a Matlab and other programming languages use double-floating point precision for decimal numbers. This format uses up to 64 bits to store each decimal number: 52 bits to store the digits, 11 bits to store exponents, and 1 bit to store + or -.
The 52 bits (binary digits) for the digits on their own would be enough to store numbers up to size 2^52. This is equivalent to 15 to 16 decimal digits of storage space (though some behind the scenes trickery can allow 17 digits to be stored for some numbers)
format short
log10(2^52) %52 bits gives 15 to 17 digits of precision (depending on the number)
ans = 15.6536
The 11 bits for the exponent of 10 allows for much bigger numbers, as well as very small decimals. For example, in the number 1.73e-5 (or 1.73*10^-5), these 11 bits are responsible for storing the -5 in binary, with one bit being reserved for +/-. This allows for exponents up to size 2^10, or exponents on the order of 10^3
log10(2^10)
ans = 3.0103
Combining all 63 of these bits, plus 1 more for +/-, gives us the absolute largest and smallest magnitudes Matlab can calculate:
realmax %largest number Matlab can compute
ans = 1.7977e+308
realmin
ans = 2.2251e-308
10^350 %not infinite, but larger than what Matlab can store.
ans = Inf
10^-350 %not zero, but a smaller magnitude than what Matlab can store
ans = 0
For a much more technical treatment on double-precision point precision, Wikipedia's article is a good start: Double-precision floating-point format - Wikipedia

Random number funnel to 0

Let X be an array. X(1) is a random integer between -200 and 200. If , then X(2) should be a random integer between + or - X(1) (depending on whether X(1) is positive or negative) . Repeat this process until we reach 0. What is the length of X?
x = randi([-200,200]);
X = x;
while x ~= 0
x = randi([-abs(x),abs(x)]); %abs ensures the 1st value is negative and the 2nd is positive.
X = [X x];
end
length(X)
ans = 9
X
X = 1×9
59 25 13 -6 2 1 -1 -1 0
What if we want to know the average length? And other stats? How do we simulate this?
If we copy and paste some of the code above, we can simulate the funnel experiment 1000 times.
Use Tab and Shift+Tab to move the indent on selected code right and left, respectively.
FunnelLengths = [];
numtrials = 1000;
for n = 1:numtrials
%run the experiment above as given
x = randi([-200,200]);
X = x; %restarts the funnel at just one value
while x ~= 0
x = randi([-abs(x),abs(x)]); %abs ensures the 1st value is negative and the 2nd is positive.
X = [X x];
end
%instead of just showing length(X), we append it onto FunnelLengths
FunnelLengths = [FunnelLengths length(X)];
end
 
mean(FunnelLengths)
ans = 8.1270
median(FunnelLengths)
ans = 8
max(FunnelLengths)
ans = 23
min(FunnelLengths)
ans = 2
histogram(FunnelLengths)

Note: Function files must follow the conditions below:
  • File name must start with a letter, and there are not spaces in the name at all.
  • File name must match the function name defined within.
  • Function file must either be in the same folder as your current folder, or must be "added to path" from within your current folder (Right-click a folder and select Add to path)

Function Files vs. Local Functions

Yes, you can define functions as a part of your live script. Matlab used to be more restrictive about this, but as of Matlab Version R2024a, you can define a function anywhere within your live script. (Before version R2024a, a function had to be at the very end of a script to be called).
A function defined in the middle of a live script is known as a local function.
  • Pro: You don't need a separate file for a local function.
  • Pro: You don't have to worry about the current folder or the file path.
  • Con: You can only call a local function from within the same file. You cannot call them from other files or the command window.
Whether you use a function file or a local function, functions cannot access variables from outside their code (such as from the workspace). The only way to bring variables into a function is through the inputs of the function.
function n = count_elt_matrix_alt(A, elt)
A == elt
sum(A == elt)
n = sum(sum(A == elt));
end

Practical example of a function with multiple inputs and multiple outputs
I wrote the code below for a different class. Though Math 13 has no coding, I wrote this to check the solutions to gcd and Euclidean Algorithm problems. It was helpful for writing exams, to make sure problems weren't too long.
You don't need to know anything about the code below, other than it has 6 outputs. We'll skip over the code itself and look at the results.
function [d,A,B,x,y, forward_steps] = ExtGCDCoeffs(a,b)
%Finds gcd d of a and b using euclidean algorithm,
%A shows each step of the division algorithm to find d.
%B shows each step of solving for d = ax + by.
%x and y are the coefficients required to write gcd in terms of a and b:
%d = ax + by.
 
t = 1; % Note: algorithm runs one step beyond the one that gives the gcd.
 
L(1) = max(a,b);
s(1) = min(a,b);
 
r = 1;
 
while r(end) ~= 0
d = s(t);
r(t) = mod(L(t),s(t));
q(t) = floor(L(t)./s(t));
L(t+1) = s(t);
s(t+1) = r(t);
t = t + 1;
end
 
q(t) = 0;
r(t) = 0;
A = [L',q',s',r'];
A(end, :) = [];
forward_steps = t - 1;
 
if forward_steps == 1
if a > b
x = 0;
y = 1;
else
x = 1;
y = 0;
end
B = [s(1), 0, L(1), 1, s(1)];
return
end
 
X(1) = 1;
Y(1) = -q(1);
 
if forward_steps > 2
X(2) = -q(2);
Y(2) = -q(2)*Y(1) + 1;
end
 
for k = 3:(forward_steps - 1)
X(k) = -q(k)*X(k-1) + X(k-2);
Y(k) = -q(k)*Y(k-1) + Y(k-2);
end
 
large = a*ones(forward_steps-1,1);
small = b*ones(forward_steps-1,1);
 
if a > b
B = [(r(1:(forward_steps-1)))', large, X', small, Y'];
x = X(end);
y = Y(end);
else
B = [(r(1:(forward_steps-1)))', large, Y', small, X'];
y = X(end);
x = Y(end);
end
 
end
 
a = 152;
b = 78;
[mygcd,division_arr,back_sub_arr,x,y, forward_steps] = ExtGCDCoeffs(a,b) %need array at front to get all outputs
mygcd = 2

4 2 2 0

The Extended Euclidean Algorithm writes gcd(a,b) = a*x + b*y as follows:
disp("gcd(" + a + "," + b + ") = " + mygcd + " = " + a + "(" + x + ") + " + b + "(" + y + ")")
gcd(152,78) = 2 = 152(19) + 78(-37)
This result is a big part of the Math 13 textbook. We see how the gcd is calculated (using the Euclidean Algorithm), and furthermore that the gcd of two numbers is a linear combination of those two numbers (constructed by the Extended Euclidean Algorithm).
Beyond Math 13, it's possible to study how much more efficient the Euclidean Algorithm is in finding the gcd, versus the slower method of finding all of the prime factors of both numbers. This added efficiency is especially true for larger numbers. Later in this course, we see that, even in problems we don't want to solve by hand, quicker algorithms make a huge difference in how a computer runs. This topic overall is known as complexity theory, which we study in this class. Let's look at simpler examples of complexity before returing to the Euclidean Algorithm.

Bisect Method: How calculators find roots of functions

format long
f10 = @(x) x.^2 - 10; %approx root of f10 is equivalent to approx sqrt(10)
If r is approximately a root of the function , then we want . A small magnitude means that the point is close to the x-axis, and r is approximately a root. Recall that would mean that r is a true root.
Before we talk about how the bisect method works, consider the following scenario:
Suppose we know the root is between 0 and 10, and we want accuracy up to 3 decimal places. How many points would we need to test to approximate this root? Would you guess more or less than 100 test points? More or less than 20 test points? Come up with a guess before you look at the results of the code below, no cheating. :)
tol = 10^-3;
root10 = bisect(f10,0,10,tol)
root10 =
3.162231445312500
What do you notice about the relationship between new test points and previous test points?
f10(3.125)
ans =
-0.234375000000000
f10(root10) %This value is less than 10^-3, which is what we expected.
ans =
-2.922862768173218e-04
How it works, finding the points manually.
h = @(x) x.^4 - 3.*x.^3 + 1;
X = 0:0.1:4;
plot(X,h(X),X,zeros(size(X)))
Initial guess: Root is between 0 and 1.
We know h is a continuous function. As long as h(0) and h(1) have opposite signs, we know the function must cross the x-axis somewhere on the interval [0, 1]. (Technically, this is a consequence of the Intermediate Value Theorem)
h(0) %positive
ans =
1
h(1) %negative
ans =
-1
Check the halfway point between 0 and 1. Compare the sign of h(0.5) to h(0) and h(1).
h(0.5) %positive
ans =
0.687500000000000
h(0.5) and h(1) have opposite signs, so we've guaranteed that a root exists on the smaller interval
[0.5, 1].
Check the halfway point between 0.5 and 1. Compare the sign of h(0.75) to h(0) and h(0.5).
h(0.75) %positive
ans =
0.050781250000000
h(0.75) and h(1) have opposite signs, so we've guaranteed that a root exists on the smaller interval [0.75, 1].
Check the halfway point between 0.75 and 1. Compare the sign of h(0.875) to h(0.75) and h(1).
(1 + 0.75)/2 %midpoint is the average
ans =
0.875000000000000
h(0.875) %negative
ans =
-0.423583984375000
h(0.75) and h(0.875) have opposite signs, so we've guaranteed that a root exists on the smaller interval
[0.75, 0.875].
Check the halfway point between 0.75 and 0.875. Compare the sign of h(0.8125) to h(0.75) and h(0.875).
midpt = (0.75 + 0.875)/2
midpt =
0.812500000000000
h(midpt) %negative
ans =
-0.173324584960938
h(0.75) and h(0.8125) have opposite signs, so we've guaranteed that a root exists on the smaller interval
[0.75, 0.8125].
Every time we repeat this process, the length of the interval is cut in half. This bisection of the interval into 2 halves narrows down the root very quickly. After 4 iterations, our original interval length goes from 1 to
 
r = bisect(h, 0, 1, 10^-10) %want |h(r)| < 10^-10, meaning the height of h(r) is within a distance of 10^-10 of the x-axis
r =
0.764826485945377
h(r) %it took 35 iterations, aka 35 test points, to achieve this level of accuracy.
ans =
-5.628031374271814e-11

Removing duplicates

Strategy 1: start with an all true array named keep that matches the size of your row array. Use nested loops, like with duplicate_check. If a duplicate occurs, set the later index of keep to false.
function w = duplicate_remove(v)
keep = true(size(v));
for i = 1:numel(v)
for j = i+1:numel(v)
if v(i) == v(j)
keep(j) = false; %a duplicate was found in the jth position.
%by avoiding keep(i) = false, the first instance of v(i) will
%still be in the array.
%do not return or break, we want to find multiple duplicates if
%they exist.
end
end
end
%disp(keep)
w = v(keep); %boolean indexing only keeps the indicies that are true
end
 
 
 
v_no_dupes = duplicate_remove(v)
v_no_dupes = 1×9
-2 0 -5 3 -4 2 5 1 -3
Strategy 2: Create a new list w.
For each element in v, check if that element is already in w, by using the any(any( )) functions stacked.
function w = duplicate_remove_alt(v)
w = [];
for i = 1:numel(v)
if any(any(w == v(i))) == 0 %if v(i) is not already listed in w
w = [w v(i)];
end
end
end

%N = randi([-5,5],4)

Bonus: Count how many times each element shows up in the array v.
First row of v_count is the unique list of elements in v. 2nd row is how many times these elements show up.
function v_count = count_each(v)
v_count = [v(1);sum(sum(v == v(1)))]; %make sure size of v_count is correct for later.
for i = 2:numel(v) %we already worked with v(1)
if any(any(v_count(1,:) == v(i))) == 0 %if v(i) is not already listed in v_count 1st row
pair = [v(i); sum(sum(v == v(i)))];
v_count = [v_count pair];
end
end
end

Computational Complexity, how is it measured?

Order and Big Oh notation

  • We can also say f(x) is on the order of g(x), or , in Big Oh notation, if there is some constant and where whenever
  • In other words, M*|g(x)| is eventually larger than |f(x)|.
  • f(x) and g(x) are of the same order if f(x) = O(g(x)) and g(x) = O(f(x))

Example: If , we have that quadratic order

M = 1 is too small to surpass f(x), but even M=1.5 eventually surpasses f(x) before x=50
f = @(x) x.^2 + 22.*x - 10;
g = @(x) x.^2;
X = 1:0.2:50;
 
M_vals = [1 1.2 1.5 3];
plot(X,f(X))
 
hold on
for M=M_vals
plot(X,M.*g(X), 'r')
end
legend('f(x) = x.^2 + 22.*x - 10', 'family of g(x) = M*x.^2')
hold off
Possible to see that f(x) <= 1.5x^2 within the interval [0, 50] (M = 1.5 case).
The main power term is what matters most, similar to how is finite.

Example: , but

For all , , but no matter what M > 0 we have, eventually surpasses
f = @(x) exp(x);
g = @(x) x;
X = 1:0.2:15;
 
M_vals = 10.^(0:5); %powers of 10 from 1 to 100,000
plot(X,f(X))
 
hold on
for M=M_vals
plot(X,M.*g(X), 'r')
end
legend('f(x) = e^x', 'family of g(x) = M*x')
hold off

Special Cases (smallest to largest):

  • Constant order . For instance, sin(x) = O(1), since |sin x| <= 1.
  • Logarithmic order
  • Linear order
  • Quadratic Order
  • Polynomial Order, nth degree for some integer n
  • Exponential Order

Physics example

  • .
  • . Kinetic energy is linear with respect to mass, but quadratic with respect to velocity.
  • Energy triples if mass triples, but energy is 9 times greater if velocity triples. This is why you need so much extra distance to hit the breaks if you're speeding in a car. Even going 1.4 times faster leads to almost double the amount of energy (exactly 1.96 times the energy).
A = [1.2 1.4 1.5 2 3] ;
A = [A; A.^2] %how energy increases proportionally:
A = 2×5
1.2000 1.4000 1.5000 2.0000 3.0000
1.4400 1.9600 2.2500 4.0000 9.0000
%with respect to mass vs. with respect to velocity

Complexity

  • The complexity of a program or algorithm can be measured multiple ways:
  • Time complexity: The amount of time it takes to run (on average or worst-case scenario)
  • Space complexity: The amount of memory needed to run (on average or worst-case scenario)
  • Step complexity: The number of steps it takes to run (theoretically, often worst-case scenario or with specific inputs)
  • In any case, the complexity of an algorithm is a function itself. If T(algorithm) is the time an algorithm takes to run, is linear, is quadratic, and etc.

count_sevens

Worst case timing: Requires arrays with all sevens. Algorithm will run the longest in these cases.
Check complexity based on size of array
Max_size = 20000;
len = 100:200:Max_size;

b = 7.3486e-05

ylabel("runtime (sec)")

Counting elements is a linear order algorithm, with respect to length. T(count_sevens) = O(len).
The coefficients change depening on:
  • What computer you use.
  • On a laptop/tablet, whether your device is plugged in. Mobile computers throttle processing power when not plugged in to save battery.
  • How many apps you have open (including Zoom screen share).
  • What else your computer is doing in the background. This adds an element of randomness.

Recursion, and recursive functions

A recursive function depends on its previous values:
  • 5 factorial, while 6 factorial, .
  • If f(n) = n!, then f(n) = n*f(n-1), as long as n > 1.
  • f(1) = 1! = 1
  • It's also true that f(0) = 0! = 1
function m = factorial_loop(n)
 
m = 1;
 
for i = 1:n
m = m*i
end
 
end
 
n1 = factorial_loop(9) %built with loops
m = 1
m = 2
m = 6
m = 24
m = 120
m = 720
m = 5040
m = 40320
m = 362880
n1 = 362880
factorial_arr = @(n) prod(1:n) %works properly for positive integers
factorial_arr = function_handle with value:
@(n)prod(1:n)
factorial_arr(9)
ans = 362880
function m = factorial_rec(n)
 
if n == 0 %initial value of recursion
%test_if = n
m = 1;
%disp("initial value case has been resolved")
else
%test_else = n
m = n*factorial_rec(n-1);
%disp("case " + n + " has been resolved")
end
 
end
 
n2 = factorial_rec(9) %built with recursion, no loops at all
n2 = 362880

Each row of Pascal's Triangle Depends on the previous row.
nchoosek_closed = @(n,k) factorial(n)/(factorial(k)*factorial(n-k)) % n!/(k!*(n-k)!)
nchoosek_closed = function_handle with value:
@(n,k)factorial(n)/(factorial(k)*factorial(n-k))
c_closed = nchoosek_closed(8,4) %exercise
c_closed = 70
 
function c = nchoosek_rec(n,k)
 
if k == 0 || k == n %k == 0 is the left edge of triangle, k == n is the right edge.
c = 1;
else
c = nchoosek_rec(n-1,k-1) + nchoosek_rec(n-1, k);
end
 
end
 
c_recurse = nchoosek_rec(8,4)
c_recurse = 70
n = 8;
Row = [];
for k=0:n
Row = [Row nchoosek_rec(n,k)];
end
Row
Row = 1×9
1 8 28 56 70 56 28 8 1
 
(In homework) Finding the greatest common divisor (gcd) of two numbers has an interesting recursion. This method is actually a lot more efficient computationally than checking all prime factors.
%aside for how to swap variables
a = 8
a = 8
b = 7
b = 7
temp = a
temp = 8
a = b
a = 7
b = temp
b = 8
 
mod(8,7) %8 = 1*7 + 1. mod(8,7) gives the remainder in this equation.
ans = 1
mod(52, 14) %52 = 3*14 + 10. Remainder of division for 52 / 14
ans = 10
 
function d = gcd_recursion(a, b)
%Want a and b integers, where a >= b.
if a < b %when a < b, swap them
temp = a;
a = b;
b = temp;
end %Now we guarantee a >= b
 
%Instead of the if statement above, it's also possible to
%define new variables M = max(a,b), m = min(a,b), and
%replace a and b below with M and m.
 
if b == 0
d = a;
else
r = mod(a, b)
d = gcd_recursion(b, r);
end
 
 
end
 
 
ourgcd = gcd_recursion(152,20)
r = 12
r = 8
r = 4
r = 0
ourgcd = 4
